        <briefdescription>
<para>returns the power product of <computeroutput>pw</computeroutput> and <computeroutput>qw</computeroutput>. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>Let <formula id="105">$ {p}^{(w)}=(p,w_p), p\in\mathbb{R}^3, w_p\in\mathbb{R}$</formula> and <formula id="106">$ {q}^{(w)}=(q,w_q), q\in\mathbb{R}^3, w_q\in\mathbb{R}$</formula> be two weighted points.</para>
<para>The <emphasis>power product</emphasis>, also called <emphasis>power distance</emphasis> between <formula id="98">$ {p}^{(w)}$</formula> and <formula id="99">$ {q}^{(w)}$</formula> is defined as <formula id="100">\[ \Pi({p}^{(w)},{q}^{(w)}) = {\|{p-q}\|^2-w_p-w_q} \]</formula> where <formula id="101">$ \|{p-q}\|$</formula> is the Euclidean distance between <formula id="102">$ p$</formula> and <formula id="103">$ q$</formula>.</para>
<para>The weighted points <formula id="98">$ {p}^{(w)}$</formula> and <formula id="99">$ {q}^{(w)}$</formula> are said to be <emphasis>orthogonal</emphasis> iff <formula id="104">$ \Pi{({p}^{(w)},{q}^{(w)})}
= 0$</formula>.</para>
<para>Four weighted points have, in 3D, a unique common orthogonal weighted point called the <emphasis>power sphere</emphasis>. The weighted point orthogonal to three weighted points in the plane defined by these three points is called the <emphasis>power circle</emphasis>. The <emphasis>power segment</emphasis> will denote the weighted point orthogonal to two weighted points on the line defined by these two points. </para>
        </detaileddescription>
